<section>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Nobody fully trusts the calorie number on a treadmill screen — and honestly, they shouldn't. Most built-in consoles have no idea what the person running on them actually weighs. They don't know how old they are. And whatever incline adjustment they claim to make is rarely backed by any meaningful exercise science. That "623 calories burned" sitting there at the end of a run? More like 480, if the person weighs less than the machine assumes.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    This treadmill calorie calculator does things differently. It runs on the <a href="https://www.acsm.org/education-resources/books/guidelines-exercise-testing-prescription" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ACSM treadmill metabolic equation</a> — the same framework exercise physiologists use in clinical and research settings — paired with validated MET values from established exercise science databases. Weight, age, gender, speed, incline, and session duration all go into it, because they all genuinely affect the outcome. There's also a Pace &amp; Distance tab for working out splits before or after a run, and a MET reference table to see exactly where any speed-and-incline combination sits on the effort spectrum.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">What Is a Treadmill Calorie Calculator and How Does It Work?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Most online calorie calculators for treadmills are surprisingly basic — weight, speed, time, done. That's a problem, because speed and time alone explain only part of what drives energy expenditure. Incline changes everything. So is the difference between a 25-year-old and a 55-year-old running at the same pace. So does the biological sex of the person doing the running.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    This calculator uses the ACSM treadmill metabolic equation, which splits the workload into two components. The first is <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">horizontal work</span> — the energy cost of simply moving the body forward at a given belt speed. The second is <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">vertical work</span> — the additional energy needed to lift body mass against gravity when the treadmill is inclined. Both components contribute to oxygen consumption (VO₂), which then converts to a MET value, which then converts to calories via:
  </p>
  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    Calories = MET × Weight (kg) × Time (hours)
  </div>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Age and gender sit on top of that as a correction layer through a heart rate-based formula. Two people with the same weight, running the same speed for the same time, can genuinely burn different amounts of energy depending on age and sex — because lean body mass proportions and cardiovascular efficiency aren't identical across those groups. Skipping those fields, as plenty of calculators let users do, quietly introduces errors that stack up across weeks of tracking.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Use This Treadmill Calorie Calculator</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Three tabs sit at the top of the tool. Each one is independent — use whichever fits the session.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Tab 1: Calorie Burn</h3>
