  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">What Is MET and Why Does the Calculator Use It?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    MET — <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Metabolic Equivalent of Task</span> — is how exercise scientists put a consistent number on the energy cost of any given activity. Sitting at rest equals exactly 1 MET, defined as roughly 3.5 ml of oxygen consumed per kilogram of bodyweight per minute. Everything else gets expressed as a multiple of that baseline.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Walking slowly at 2.5 km/h is around MET 2.5 — about two and a half times resting effort. Jogging at 8 km/h on a flat treadmill comes in at MET 8.3, meaning the body is running through oxygen more than eight times faster than at rest. Hit 11–12 km/h and MET jumps into the 11–12.5 range.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Where MET gets really interesting is on the incline. A 4 km/h walk on flat ground is a casual MET 3.0. That same walking speed on a 10% grade bumps to MET 5.3. At 15% incline it reaches 6.8 — which crosses into moderate-to-vigorous territory by any standard clinical definition, and it's still just walking. It's exactly why steep incline programs like the 12-3-30 (12% grade, 3 mph, 30 minutes) keep pulling people in. The calorie burn is real, the knees mostly aren't complaining, and it doesn't require the fitness base that actual running demands.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The MET values in the reference table come directly from the <a href="https://pacompendium.com" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Compendium of Physical Activities</a> — the database that exercise science research has used as its standard reference for energy expenditure categorization for decades.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">What Actually Affects Calorie Burn on a Treadmill?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Two people can run side by side on identical machines at identical speeds for identical time — and their real calorie burns can be 30% apart. The formula isn't being imprecise; it's accurately reflecting the fact that calorie burn is personal. Here's what's driving the difference.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Body Weight</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Weight dominates the calculation more than any other variable. Every extra kilogram of body mass costs energy to move forward, and even more energy to move upward on an incline. A 90 kg runner burns roughly 25–30% more than a 70 kg runner at the same speed, grade, and duration — every single session. This is the reason treadmill console estimates without weight input are mostly fiction. They're guessing, and the guess is usually flattering.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Speed</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    More speed means more calories, but the relationship isn't proportional — it's more like exponential at the higher end. The jump from 6 km/h walking to 8 km/h jogging isn't just a moderate step up in effort. It's a full gait change — from walking mechanics to running mechanics — and the energy cost reflects that. Then going from 8 to 10 km/h adds even more proportionally than the 6-to-8 jump did. Speed compounds.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Incline</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Most people either ignore the incline field entirely or wildly underestimate what it does. Flat treadmill running only covers horizontal work. The moment any grade gets added, vertical work enters — legs now lifting body mass against gravity with every stride, not just pushing it forward. One percent of incline adds roughly 4–5% to calorie burn at walking speeds. That might sound minor. But go from 0% to 10%, and calorie burn at a walking pace starts approaching jogging territory. Go to 15%, and a moderate walk is clinically vigorous exercise. Grade is probably the most underused lever in treadmill training.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Age</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The age correction is a little counterintuitive. Resting metabolic rate does decline with age, but that's not really what's being captured here. For a given workload — same speed, same incline — older adults tend to have a higher relative heart rate because the heart is working closer to its declining maximum capacity. The calorie formula adjusts for that cardiovascular demand. It's not a huge correction, but it's real, and ignoring it makes the estimate slightly less accurate for anyone over 40.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Gender</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Men and women burn different amounts of calories at the same objective workload, and it's not about effort or fitness level — it's physiology. Average lean body mass is higher in men, resting metabolic rate is higher in men, and cardiovascular oxygen delivery tends to be more efficient on average. The result: a man typically burns somewhat more calories than a woman of equal weight at the same speed and incline. This calculator applies separate formulas for each. They're population averages — a trained woman can absolutely outburn a sedentary man at the same inputs — but the distinction matters for most people.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Duration</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Simple one. Double the time, roughly double the calories. For any steady-state session at consistent speed and incline, it's close enough to linear for planning purposes. The one thing the formula doesn't capture is <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">EPOC</span> — the post-exercise calorie burn that follows high-intensity work — but that effect is real mainly at very high intensities, and it's modest in magnitude compared to the session burn itself.
  </p>

