<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How Accurate Is This Calculator?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Pretty accurate for what it's designed to do — which is steady-state treadmill exercise at consistent speed and incline. The ACSM equation is <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7994759/" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium" target="_blank" rel="noopener">validated for steady-state exercise</a>, and under those conditions estimates typically land within 10–15% of directly measured energy expenditure in healthy adults. That's a much tighter window than a console that's ignoring weight, age, and gender entirely.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    A few things genuinely reduce the accuracy, and they're worth knowing:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Handrail use.</span> People don't realize how much this matters. Even resting fingers lightly on the rails while walking a steep incline transfers some bodyweight off the legs and onto the arms. Real muscular work drops. The formula assumes zero rail contact throughout the session — someone who holds on regularly is burning notably less than the estimate.</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Intervals.</span> The ACSM equation assumes the body is at a metabolic steady state at the input speed and incline. Interval training — alternating speed or grade — never fully settles at any single state. The estimate becomes a useful approximation rather than a precise figure. Not useless, just less tight.</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Individual metabolic variation.</span> Running economy, how efficiently muscles use oxygen, cardiovascular fitness, even genetic factors — all of these produce real variation between individuals at the same objective inputs. Population-level spread of ±10–15% is normal even with perfectly accurate data entry. Some people will consistently burn more than the estimate, some less.</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Machine accuracy.</span> Older treadmills or poorly maintained ones can have belt speeds or incline readings that don't quite match reality. The calculator uses whatever numbers get entered. If the machine's display is slightly wrong, the estimate will be too.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    None of this is a reason to distrust the tool — it's a reason to use it consistently and watch for trends, which is more useful than agonizing over whether any single session estimate is off by 5%.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Does Incline Walking Actually Burn as Many Calories as Running?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    It can — genuinely — and a lot of people find this surprising because running feels harder. But "harder" and "more calories" aren't always the same thing, and steep incline changes the equation significantly.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Here's the actual comparison for a 70 kg person over 30 minutes:
  </p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm text-slate-600 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-800 font-semibold">
          <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Activity</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Speed</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Incline</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Est. MET</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Est. Calories</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
