        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Walking at 15% incline at 4.8 km/h gets within shouting distance of flat jogging in calorie terms — no running involved. For anyone managing knee issues, coming back from injury, or who simply doesn't enjoy running but still wants the burn, that's genuinely useful to know. The knees handle incline walking much more kindly than running does.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The catch is the posterior chain. Calves, Achilles, hamstrings — they take on a lot at 12–15% grade. Going from zero incline to 15% in one session and holding it for 45 minutes is how people end up limping around for a week. Building up over a few weeks is the sensible approach.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Treadmill vs. Outdoor Running — Is There a Real Calorie Difference?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Yes, and it's not trivial. Outdoor running at the same speed generally burns somewhere around 5–10% more calories than treadmill running — and there are a few legitimate reasons for it.
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Wind resistance is real,</span> even at moderate running speeds. Outside, every stride is happening against air, which adds a small but consistent metabolic cost that simply doesn't exist on a still indoor machine.</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Outdoor terrain is never perfectly flat or uniform.</span> The stabilizer muscles — ankle, hip, core — are making constant micro-adjustments on real ground that a predictable treadmill belt never demands. Over a long run, that accumulates.</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">The belt itself is genuinely debated.</span> The prevailing view in exercise science is that a moving belt slightly assists the hamstring's role in pulling the foot back during each stride, making treadmill running mechanically fractionally easier than overground running at the same speed.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The standard fix is well-established: set the treadmill to 1% incline. That single adjustment, from a <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8887211/" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1996 Journal of Sports Sciences study that's been widely cited ever since</a>, approximately offsets the metabolic difference between treadmill and flat outdoor running.
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    What this calculator produces is treadmill-specific. For outdoor running at the same pace, expect actual burn to run a bit higher.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How Many Calories Does a 30-Minute Treadmill Session Burn?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Without question the most Googled treadmill question in existence. The real answer is that it depends enormously — on the person's weight, on how fast they're going, on the incline. But for a 70 kg (154 lb) person, here's what 30 minutes at various intensities actually looks like:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Slow walk (4 km/h, flat):</span> ~105–120 kcal</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Brisk walk (6 km/h, flat):</span> ~165–180 kcal</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Incline walk (4.8 km/h, 10%):</span> ~200–215 kcal</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Light jog (7–8 km/h, flat):</span> ~240–280 kcal</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Moderate run (9–10 km/h, flat):</span> ~310–355 kcal</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Fast run (11–12 km/h, flat):</span> ~370–420 kcal</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    At 85 kg, add roughly 20% to all of these. At 55 kg, subtract roughly 20%. These figures come from the same ACSM-based formula the calculator runs on — not from a treadmill console guessing in the dark. For a specific session at a specific weight, the Calorie Burn tab above gives the exact number in a few seconds.
  </p>

